Observations
On a small, well-structured tabular dataset like Titanic, the deep network offers little to no advantage over the basic single-hidden-layer model — both converge to similar AUC values, confirming that added depth mostly increases capacity without extracting new signal from simple features.
Errors are not uniformly distributed across the population: both models struggle most with third-class passengers and with males who actually survived, reflecting the underlying class imbalance and the dominance of the sex and class features in driving predictions.
Regularization (alpha) has the most visible effect among the swept hyperparameters, with AUC degrading sharply once alpha climbs past roughly 0.1 as the model is pushed toward underfitting, while very small values give essentially identical performance.
The deep network is noticeably more sensitive to learning rate than the basic one, with high learning rates causing unstable convergence, whereas the basic model remains stable across a wider range — a typical symptom of deeper architectures needing more careful tuning.
The predicted probability distributions show both models are reasonably well-calibrated around the 0.5 threshold, but a cluster of confident false negatives (survivors predicted to die with very low probability) suggests the models over-rely on sex and class and miss atypical survival cases that would likely benefit from richer feature engineering rather than more layers.
